ngdom","Newham,Warwickshire,England":"Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Purifoy","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Altered form of English   Purefoy  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Purefoy","meanings":["English: from Anglo-Norman French <i>par fei</i> ‘by (my) faith’, a nickname for someone who habitually used this expression. Compare   Purifoy  . This surname is very rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Peurifoy","meanings":["Altered form of   Purifoy  , itself an altered form of English   Purefoy  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William Purifoy I was born about 1293, in Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom as the son of Philip Purefoy. He had at least 1 son with Mrs. Alice Purifoy. He died in 1332, at the age of 40."},"et":{"Abt 1293–1332":"umbes 1293–1332","1293–1332":"1293–1332","1295–Female":"1295–Surnud","1312–1374":"1312–1374","1260–1322":"1260–1322","Abt 1293":"umbes 1293","1312":"1312","1322":"1322","1332":"1332","Aft 1322":"pärast 1322","1374":"1374","1295":"1295","1260":"1260","1293":"1293","Misterton, Leicestershire, England":"Shelford, Warwickshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Newham,Warwickshire,England":"Warwickshir